description.text:
This is a replica of the visor worn by Levar Burton as Geordi Laforge on Star Trek: The Next Generation.
There were several versions, and these aren't perfect to any of them. But they're close...

I had more detailed instructions here, but when I uploaded another file they were erased. So, sorry if these aren't detailed, but I don't feel like typing them again. Feel free to ask me any questions.
  • Print out both parts
  • While they're printing, cut 50, 7/8" pieces of 1/8" diameter brass rod or tube. It's available at hobby lobby in the model train area. You'll probably need 2 packages of 3, 12" pieces.
    3.Sand and fill the 2 printed pieces to your liking.
    4.Glue the rods in the holes of 1 side only. You might have to redrill the holes, I did.
    5.Glue the rods into the other side.
    6.Glue, or use filler to close the gap (if any) between the two pieces.
    7.Sand and fill all cracks, then sand some more until you're happy with the finish.
    8.Mask the brass rods with tape. I used blue painters tape, it worked well.
    9.Paint, then I recommend a clear coat as well.
  • (Optional) Find an event where Levar Burton is appearing, and have him sign them!
    • Enjoy!

title: Creative Zen Mosaic Handlebar Clamp and clip

description.text:
Had a friend that wanted to mount his Creative Zen Mosiac MP3 player on his Harley and then plug it into the stereo amp.  
I scratch-designed this in Autodesk Inventor and then printed it in ABS on a Makerbot 2X.  The Zen player "pops" into the holder and can be released by pushing through the hole in the back of the clip.  It will NOT vibrate out.  
The handlebar clamp must be printed in ABS or PET+ or a similar material for the "living hinge" to work.  PVA would be too brittle.  When done in ABS or PET+ the living hinge will open far enough to go around the bar, and then can be clamped with the hardware.  I wouldn't do this too many times if using ABS though, it will ultimately turn white and fail.  PET+ is less of a problem.

I printed this in ABS at 101% to compensate for shrink.  It would be better to print the handlebar clamp in PET+ (or a similar flexible material) if you have it.  
The hardware is all 6-32 stainless, although there are probably metric fasteners that will come close enough to work.

comments.text: As with all tight tolerance parts made with ABS, don't forget to adjust your scaling for shrinkage.  On my 2X these parts were printed at 101%.

description.text:
This is the long awaited 6x6 120 version of my tiny pinhole camera. The assembly instructions are exactly the same as the tiny pinhole camera https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2498620 except for the added film number viewer at the back. This film viewer is just a simple blade with a knob that slides up and down in the groove at the back of the camera, simply glue the knob onto the blade and you're good to go.

I took some test shots on a roll of Fomapan 400, which i developed in ID68, then promptly scratched with my squeegee drying tool... the emulsion on Fomapan is incredibly soft I discovered! But this should give a good idea of what you're in for, there is a bit of vignetting around the corners which I think is customary for the pinhole experience :-) I metered for an f-stop of 500 with what I thought was a small, yet still practical pinhole size, so this should be a good base point for you to start form.

Enjoy people! And feel free to make suggestions for new designs or improvements, you can even leave a tip if you like the design enough :-)
scale box for offroad scael trucks

This is my overengineered project to learn OpenSCAD and MakerBot Customizer. It will hold a V4 microswitch on to V-slot and presumably T-slot or any flat surface with a screw hole.

You can choose switch orientation, which side(s) or rear corner(s) you want the wires to exit from, mounting behind the switch or to an adjacent rail, and various other things I thought to try while adding switches to my printer. If the customizer options are insufficient, there are more variables in the OpenSCAD code to tweak - and it is certainly possible to find configurations which are not useful.

title: Modular Wall Spool Holder / Porta Bobine a muro modulare

description.text:
Con l'aumentare delle mie stampanti ho sentito il bisogno di organizzare meglio i porta bobine che erano sparsi sul banco da lavoro. Non trovando nulla che mi convincesse totalmente ho deciso di disegnarmi un portabobine che soddisfacesse le mie esigenze:

  • montaggio a parete
  • possibilità di cambiare rapidamente una singola bobina per volta senza doverle rimuovere tutte
  • asse di rotazione centralizzato rispetto alla bobina
  • sicurezza di ridurre al minimo gli sforzi durante prelievo del filamento da parte della stampante (grazie ai cuscinetti ed ai cappuccetti per le barre filettate)

Ho pensato di riutilizzare il più bossibile delle cose che avevo in casa, le barre filettate M8 sono infatti quelle che erano presenti nei kit delle stampanti in mio possesso.
Le barre filettate da me utilizzate sono lunghe 160mm vi sconsiglio di utilizzare barre più corte perchè potreste incontrare problemi con alcuni tipi di bobine, se ne avete la possibilità utilizzate barre lunghe circa 180mm.
I fori utilizzati per il fissaggio al muro sono ø4.5mm così anche nel caso in cui la vostra stampante non sia calibrata al meglio non dovreste incontrare problemi usando viti ø4mm.

Occorrente:

  • Barre filettate M8 http://amzn.to/2yvzvYL oppure http://amzn.to/2fubWZe
  • Tasselli per viti M4 (Lunghezza vite almeno 30mm)
  • Cuscinetti a sfera 608 (øinterno 8mm øesterno 22mm spessore 7mm) scegliete il più economico http://amzn.to/2ftgDlX

Onestamente vi consiglio di comprare tutto da un ferramenta o in un qualsiasi brico._

description.text:
I'd spent untold countless hours playing Battlefield 2142 back in the day, and was always fascinated with the walkers. Who doesn't want to run around shooting bad guys with a giant robot?

Using all the reference pics I could find, as well as some images of a well-made fan model (sadly, his image is available via google, but it looks like Sadguyd8's DeviantArt page is down at the moment) and a pepakura file I've had floating around my hard drive for years - (available here https://goo.gl/N1iSji ) I decided to build one, using Fusion360 to model it. I tried to keep as close to the original as I could, both in scaling and shape, but some parts of it have been smoothed out to be a little more realistic, at least in my opinion.
The top turret, mini-guns, upper to lower torso joint, and legs are all movable/posable. all the part interactions are modeled at a .2mm gap, so if your tolerances are off, it may end up being a static display.My printer isn't super tuned, but I can get decent prints out of it, and had no issues with fitting things together. Also, this thing is large! the upper torso measures 91/2 long. Smaller printers will probably need to have some parts re-split. If it's needed, leave a message and I'll upload them when I can.

This is still a work in progress, but is mostly complete. As i sit down and write this, I'm in the process of printing the lower half of the legs. As such, everything above that is printable, and I'll modify and update if I run into any issues in the interim.
As a side note, I chose not to print the barrels of the two mini-guns. I used 2mm OD aluminum tubing I'd purchased from a local hobby shop. Enough tubing to complete both mini-guns was approx $3 US. each barrel is 64mm in length, which I cut using a hobby saw blade for my X-acto without problems. I have not included a printable barrel, but again, its something I can add if someone wants it.

I've also included a .zip file with all the parts, broken down by what goes where. I find it makes it a lot easier to print multi-part files, hopefully you do too.

UPDATE!: I've re-uploaded the parts at the correct sizing. Its currently 400% of the originally uploaded size. If you have an SLA printer, you could probably get away with the smaller size, but I'm not that cool :p
I've also broken the top turret into easier to print parts, and separated out some parts of the main body and lower torso. The legs are working, I have finished the left leg, and have the right leg printed, it just needs cleanup and assembly. I may do some more modification on the foot, as the shield currently hits on the lower leg when swung fully forward, and I'd like to be able to change the mount of the shield to prevent this. I also intend on adding some 'snap-stops' to the knee and lower leg, allowing it to be posed like an action figure. I have them modeled in the torso to upper leg, and they work correctly. Without adding them to the other parts of the leg though, they don't hold position well, especially with the main body weight on them. As is, its currently completely printable, but there are some modifications I'd like to make to increase its 'posability'. I'll upload pics as soon as I've finished assembly, which will be in a couple days (work calls, and I don't have a lot of free time when I'm working).

UPDATE 2!: Its finished, and fully printable. I'll update the legs at some point in the future to be posable. For now, you'll need to glue them. I was hoping a friction fit would be enough to hold a pose, but the weight of the upper body is too much, and it ends up sagging into 'park'. I'll need to make some significant modifications to get this to work correctly, but for now, it makes a decent (and HUGE) static display/model. I've learned a ton doing this, and I'll keep fine tuning it as I learn more.

This is my 3rd or 4th iteration made in Fusion360, and the first truly printable one. I'm still in the progress of printing the legs, so there may be updated parts for this as I discover any issues.

This FPV camera protector for the GEPRC LX5/LSX5 Leopard and complementary GoPro mount is a bit of a Frankenstein. If you do not need the GoPro mount, I recommend the thing by Zytra (linked below), as it is what I used for inspiration and validation of measurements.

I designed this such that the GoPro mount fully attaches to the top standoff and the FPV camera protector sits on top of/outside of the GoPro mount. It all goes together securely to my satisfaction. You'll need 1 additional 20mm round standoff for the rear of the GoPro mount. Additionally, I wanted to be able to swap the GoPro in and out of the mount easily, so I added slots for securing the front of the mount with zip ties. Otherwise, it is a bear to insert or remove.

I expect the FPV camera protector works best with the side plates I remixed.

I used several things as inspiration and measurement validation, but all objects were built new. The key piece that helped me was the Fusion360 source file linked by joem_ in his Session mount thing. This provided an accurate model of the metal pod for the LX5 to build from.

description.text:
So the factory cooling fan location and functionality was badly thought out and pretty pathetic (being polite)
After dialing in the printer just right and getting the print speeds cranked up I was getting overheating of the mosfets on long print runs, so i decided to check another mod off my 'To do' list.

'Complete Case v23' is just for thingiview purposes!

  1. Its a multi part print to shorten printing time,
  2. All parts interlock and require gluing,
  3. The 'Bottom' panel has a larger cutout to allow for the usb and power connecter to run through.
  4. The usb requires plugging in before mounting the board as it is snug against the bottom panel to stop me from inadvertently working it loose because i'm forever unplugging the printer from my laptop!
  5. The control board needs to have the plastic stand-offs removed and then remounts directly onto the base plate.
  6. I used 25mm M3's, nuts & washers to mount the board and case in its original location. You can use shorter screws but thats all i had laying around.
  7. Dont use a washer on the bottom right mounting hole (board side) as it will short on the 2 smd leds just above the hole!
  8. I designed the case extra deep to allow for 40x40x20mm fans to be fitted, however i came across a spare 40x40x10mm so used that along with the original cooling fan!
  9. The 'Front' panel doubles as your cable tidy area and has a load of slots allowing for a liberal use of cable ties.
  10. I had run out of steam by the time i got to "how to attach the lid"... My apologies, this leaves something to be desired!
    I had originally intended to just use some very short M3's and screw directly into the end panels, but because it is a very close tolerance i found that the clips friction fit nice and tight with no issues! (mines been on 2 months now and still hasn't moved with both fans permanently on!)
  11. Although i used some previously printed grilles on mine, I have also included my fan grille design, i'd recommend printing that in 0.1mm layer height!
  12. I have included the f3d & iges files, so please feel free to tweak and add your own input to this design!

Whilst this is not a re-work there was some initial inspiration from Lukie80's case design (namely the honeycomb design vents and the cutout style base plate to shorten printing time a little!)

I think you mounted this upside down.
By far the most heat generated on this board comes from the Mosfets that drive the heated bed, and the print head/s.
Therefore, since heat rises, to prevent these devices cooking the rest of the board, I would make sure that they are near the top, and preferably close to an unobscured grill
Also make absolutely certain that no cabling can possibly come into physical contacts with these devices (hot,hot,HOT)
I speak from expensive experience :@)

And I didn't really want to make up a new power lead .
The fans are now located directly over the stepper drivers and mosfets respectively and as the case is pretty much sealed it does now create a forced air flow over these. The original open mounting of the board and really poor factory location of the fan meant there was no force air reaching the mosfets at all, they were nothing more than passively cooled at best.

description.text: UPDATE Haydn Huntley created a new version of the carriage and has been kind enough to publish it. Please check out his carriage at: https://www.youmagine.com/designs/improved-kossel-carriage-for-deltaprintr-or-graber-wheels-and-1515-extrusions For the original carriage design that used cheap nylon rollers: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:215438 Note, his is meant for the Grabber rollers or the Delta Printer rollers. At some point, I'll make a prime line version and repost here. Wing. UPDATE: Temporarily removing the files as I have been notified and confirmed that there is an offset in the bolt mount holes, which will result in a tilt to the carriage when installed. :( Will repost once I have a new file that doesn't have that issue. Description I really liked ElectronicHacks' "Kossel Mini Prime Line Roller Carriage"! The use of the low cost nylon prime line rollers is awesome! However, I found that when I printed them straight up, there was some slack, even after fully tightening. To the point I needed to file away some material to get it to latch onto the HFS3-1515 aluminum extrusions. So after the 2nd one, I remade the model from ElectronicHacks' Sketchup file and removed some material so that the compression arm can come in another 1mm. This is a vertical motion carriage for HFS3-1515 aluminum extrusions like those sold by Misumi. I've included both the modified SketchUp file (forgot the extension) and the exported STL file.
For printing, I sliced the STL file in Kisslicer, though any slicer should work fine.

• 1.75mm PLA
  • UBIS ceramic hot end 1.75mm @ 215 celsius
  • Ceramic tile + painters tape print bed
  • 20-40mm/sec perimeter and fill speeds.
  • .2032mm layer heights (I'm using 1/4-20 threaded rod)
  • 215 degrees celsius print temp (PLA)
  • 0.8mm wall thickness
  • 33.3% infill

• 2.5mm Hex Allen Wrench (will fit the M3 hex socket)
  • M3 hex socket tool (like that used with Makerbeam/etc.) Should be deep enough to handle M3-20 bolts.
  • Needle nose pliers, for the square nuts.

description.header: Assembly was done with the following parts:
description.text:
• 3 x Prime Line Nylon Rollers (they come in boxes of 2 or 4)(M-6153 Prime-Line Nylon Rollers)
  • 3 x M3-20mm hex socket head bolts.
  • 3 x M3 sqaure nuts
  • 3 x M3 locking nuts with nylon
  • 1 x M3-10mm hex socket head bolt

• Print the carriage
  • Thread the M3-20(s) through the three roller mounting holes. The socket head should rest inside of the recess.
  • Screw on the M3 square nut tightly.
  • Slide the Nylon roller, nut side down. The edges of the nut will rest on the corners of the M3 square nut.
  • Screw on the locking nut with nylon, tighten the whole stack.
  • Repeat for the other two rollers.
    • The M3 socket tool and allen wrench will come in handy to tighten everything nicely. The M3-10 will be threaded into the side to compress the arm and get the rollers to grab onto the HFS3-1515. I ream out the side hole with a narrow tipped scissor. A file, drill, or other similar tool would work to ream out the hole a bit to avoid splitting the print by forcing the bolt. The unit should grip the HFS3-1515 nicely and still roll freely or with some friction, depending on the level of tightness. The GT2 grip and other bits should be pulled from the original Mini Kossel files and are thus not included here.

description.text: Mickey Glove cookie cutter, 8cm long.

comments.text:
I love this cookie cutter! I'm using it this year to make holiday gingerbread cookies.
I did notice one thing that might help others who have a printer like mine (Qidi Tech I).
It looks like the cookie cutter's cutting edge is very close to 1mm thick when printing at 100%. My printer nozzle is 0.4mm wide (and won't multiply evenly to 1mm) so I will need to scale this just a little so there won't be a hollow gap inside the walls of the cookie cutter (I need the wall to be either 0.8mm or 1.2mm wide to eliminate the gap). My printer can't perform an infill in a gap that's less than 0.4mm wide, so a gap is left in there and it's not filled in when it gets to the top of the print.
If anyone else uses a printer with a 0.4mm nozzle, try scaling it up or down until the wall is either 0.8mm thick or 1.2mm thick and there won't be a gap.

This is a 120mm fan holder to be coupled to one of the vertical side rails on a TEVO Tarantula 3D printer.

M42 P66 S0 ;turn cooling fan off
M140 S0 ; turn off bed temperature
G1 Y200 F10000 ;move completed part out
